        <h2>When to choose Buildertrend</h2>
        <p>Buildertrend is the right choice when you need an end-to-end platform for managing residential construction from estimate to final payment. If you're a custom homebuilder or remodeling contractor who wants to manage client communication, change orders, financials, scheduling, and subs in one system, Buildertrend covers it all.</p>

        <p>The reasons to choose Buildertrend over Fieldwire:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>You need a client portal for homeowners to approve selections and change orders</li>
          <li>You want budget vs. actual tracking integrated with your project data</li>
          <li>You're replacing multiple tools (spreadsheets, email, separate scheduling) with one system</li>
          <li>You do primarily residential work where Buildertrend's features are purpose-built</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>Buildertrend</strong> — Full project management for residential builders. From first estimate to final payment in one platform.</p>
          <a href="https://www.buildertrend.com" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank" class="btn">Visit Buildertrend →</a>
        </div>

        <h2>When to choose Fieldwire</h2>
        <p>Fieldwire is the right choice when your primary need is field coordination — getting current drawings to the field team, managing punch lists, tracking issues, and enabling subs to work from their phones without navigating a complex PM system.</p>

        <p>The reasons to choose Fieldwire:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>You're a commercial GC who already has Procore (or similar) for PM but needs better field tools</li>
          <li>Your subs need drawing access without needing access to your full project data</li>
          <li>Punch list management and plan markup are your primary field challenges</li>
          <li>You want a free option for small projects (Fieldwire's free tier covers 3 active projects)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Can you use both?</h2>
        <p>Yes — and many contractors do. A common pattern for commercial GCs is Procore for full project management + Fieldwire for field coordination. The same logic applies for some residential contractors: Buildertrend for office/client-facing work + Fieldwire for superintendents and subs who need drawing-centric field access.</p>

        <p>That said, for pure residential builders, Buildertrend's built-in field features (daily logs, progress photos, task assignments) are usually sufficient without adding Fieldwire. The "use both" approach makes more sense for commercial work where drawing management depth matters.</p>

        <h2>Pricing reality</h2>
        <p>Fieldwire's per-user pricing ($39–$54/user/mo on paid plans) can add up for larger teams. For a team of 10 field users, that's $390–$540/mo — comparable to Buildertrend's $499/mo flat rate for unlimited users. At that point, the comparison shifts from price to capability fit.</p>

        <p>Fieldwire's free tier (3 active projects, unlimited users) is genuinely free and functional for smaller contractors trying the tool before committing.</p>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

        <h3>Does Buildertrend have drawing management?</h3>
        <p>Buildertrend allows document and drawing uploads, but it's not a dedicated drawing management system. You can share PDFs and link documents to projects, but it doesn't offer Fieldwire's version control, markup tools, or plan-linked punch lists. If drawing management is a priority, Fieldwire (or Procore's drawing tools) are meaningfully better.</p>

        <h3>Is Fieldwire good for residential construction?</h3>
        <p>Yes, but it's overkill for simple residential projects. Where Fieldwire shines in residential is for larger custom homes or commercial-adjacent projects where detailed drawing management and punch list tracking matter. Most residential builders will find Buildertrend's integrated tools more relevant to their day-to-day needs.</p>

        <h3>What are Fieldwire's limitations?</h3>
        <p>Fieldwire doesn't manage financials (budgets, invoicing, change orders), doesn't have a client portal, and isn't a scheduling tool in the CPM sense. It's a field coordination tool — excellent at what it does, but not designed to be a contractor's primary project management platform.</p>

